<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1437,1969,2033]" lastBlockId="56.[151,1437,152,863]" lastPageId="56" lastPageNumber="57" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,308,1969,1996]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<typeStatus box="[151,210,1970,1996]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Type</typeStatus>
species:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo, 2019" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo" authorityYear="2019" box="[316,545,1971,1996]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Riseriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="santosae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[316,545,1971,1996]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Riseriopsis santosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[552,612,1971,1997]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,2005,2032]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Fauveliopsids with body cylindrical, slightly swollen anteriorly, markedly swollen posteriorly. Anterior and posterior segments short, intersegmental grooves well defined; median segments long (as long or longer as wide). Integument mostly transparent, smooth, with minute papillae mainly near pygidium. Interramal papillae small, usually with a short stalk or sessile. Noto- and neurochaetae include uni- or bidentate aciculars, straight or falcate spinulose, and smooth capillaries in anterior and posterior regions. Median chaetigers with only one notoacicular chaeta. Pygidium non-retractile, often with small papillae, and large, falcate aciculars surpassing pygidial margin. Genital papillae unknown. Free living, sometimes in flexible, fibrous tubes, with or without foreign particles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,152,863]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,405,431]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus is named to honor the late Dr. Nathan W. Riser in recognition of his careful study of one fauveliopsid species, where he clarified some anatomical features, and discovered the presence of genital papillae. The genus name is a free combination of the last name with the Greek suffix â€“ 
<emphasis box="[1032,1097,477,502]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">iopsis</emphasis>
. This suffix refers to a certain appearance or resemblance, and it was originally used for the typhloscolecid 
<taxonomicName authority="Levinsen, 1885" authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1885" box="[1011,1325,512,539]" class="Polychaeta" family="Typhloscolecidae" genus="Travisiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1011,1146,513,538]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Travisiopsis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[1153,1325,512,539]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="321 - 344" refId="ref46221" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1885) Spolia atlantica. Om nogle pelagiske Annulata. Det Kongelige Danske videnskabernes selskabs skrift- er, Naturvidenskabelig og mathematisk afdeling, Series 6, 3 (2), 321 - 344., pl. 3. Available from: http: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 34738282 (Accessed 10 Jul. 2019)" type="journal article" year="1885">Levinsen, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
matching the original meaning. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="McIntosh, W. C." box="[517,707,548,575]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 30" refId="ref46698" refString="McIntosh, W. C. (1922) Notes from the Gatty Marine Laboratory, St. Andrews, 44: 1. On new and rare Polychaeta, Gephyrea, etc., from various regions; 2. Recent additions to the British marine Polychaeta (continued). Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 9, 9, 1 - 30. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222932208632638" type="journal article" year="1922">McIntosh (1922)</bibRefCitation>
used this suffix to name what would become the 
<typeStatus box="[1274,1322,549,575]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">type</typeStatus>
genus for the family, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McIntosh" authorityYear="1922" box="[279,422,584,610]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Fauveliopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[279,422,584,610]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Fauveliopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Petersen, M. E." box="[484,661,585,611]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="491 - 515" refId="ref47148" refString="Petersen, M. E. (2000) A new genus of Fauveliopsidae (Annelida Polychaeta), with a review of its species and redescription of some described taxa. Bulletin of Marine Science, 67, 491 - 515. https: // www. ingentaconnect. com / content / umrsmas / bullmar / 2000 / 00000067 / 00000001 / art 00041? crawler = true" type="journal article" year="2000">Petersen (2000)</bibRefCitation>
followed for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Petersen" authorityYear="2000" box="[815,969,584,610]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Laubieriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[815,969,584,610]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Laubieriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The alternative would be 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Norenburg" authorityYear="1993" box="[1271,1363,585,610]" class="Anopla" genus="Riserius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Heteronemertea" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Nemertea" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1271,1363,585,610]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Riserius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it was already used by 
<bibRefCitation author="Norenburg, J. L." box="[387,590,620,647]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="203 - 205" refId="ref46947" refString="Norenburg, J. L. (1993) Riserius pugettensis gen. n., sp. n. (Nemertina: Anopla), a new mesopsammic species, and comments on phylogenetics of some anoplan characters. Hydrobiologia, 266, 203 - 205. Available from: https: // link. springer. com / article / 10.1007 / BF 00013369 https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 94 - 011 - 2052 - 4 _ 15" type="journal article" year="1993">Norenburg (1993)</bibRefCitation>
for a nemertean, such that we prefer to follow the trend for naming genera in the family.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,152,863]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,693,719]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo, 2019" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo" authorityYear="2019" box="[324,448,693,718]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Riseriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[324,448,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Riseriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[457,535,693,719]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Petersen, 2000" authorityName="Petersen" authorityYear="2000" box="[664,994,692,719]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Laubieriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[664,818,692,718]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Laubieriopsis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Petersen, M. E." box="[827,994,693,719]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="491 - 515" refId="ref47148" refString="Petersen, M. E. (2000) A new genus of Fauveliopsidae (Annelida Polychaeta), with a review of its species and redescription of some described taxa. Bulletin of Marine Science, 67, 491 - 515. https: // www. ingentaconnect. com / content / umrsmas / bullmar / 2000 / 00000067 / 00000001 / art 00041? crawler = true" type="journal article" year="2000">Petersen, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by having smooth bodies with integument usually transparent; they differ in the general body shape and in chaetal patterns. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo, 2019" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo &amp; Zhadan &amp; Rizzo" authorityYear="2019" box="[1182,1306,729,754]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Riseriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1182,1306,729,754]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Riseriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1316,1394,729,755]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the body is swollen in both ends, usually more pronounced along the posterior region, and there are only acicular notochaetae in median region, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Petersen" authorityYear="2000" box="[577,731,800,826]" class="Polychaeta" family="Fauveliopsidae" genus="Laubieriopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[577,731,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Laubieriopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the body is more or less cylindrical, not swollen in either end, and there are aciculars and capillaries in the notopodia of the median region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
